  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Deborah Weston writes this letter tonight instead of writing in her journal. She enumerates the people she&apos;s seen. Thomas Greene talked to her about &quot;the Lyceum difficulty.&quot; She gives details of this affair, which involved the refusal to sell tickets to black people. She tells of a successful meeting and names the people who gave money. They worked hard for the fair all Sunday afternoon. Deborah is glad to hear of William A. White&apos;s engagement, as &quot;it will take him out of E.G.L.&apos;s [E. G. Loring] hand &amp; put him into Mrs. Follen&apos;s more.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">The second sheet bears the address: Miss Emma Forbes Weston, 53 Federal Street, Boston, Mass. And a brief note by Deborah Weston. She mentions a steamship and that things will come on Tuesday. They may have to &quot;walk out in the face of N B &amp; it will be well to have a good bonnet on.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
